von, England"},"en":{"ABT 1300–ABT 1383":"about 1300–about 1383","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1327–1377":"1327–1377","1281–1307":"1281–1307","1283–1307":"1283–1307","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1283":"1283","1281":"1281","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","ABT 1383":"about 1383","1301":"1301","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","ABT 1300":"about 1300","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Rackheath, Norfolk County, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Rackheath, Norfolk, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, England","Whissonsett, Norfolk, England":"Whissonsett, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Yelverton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from either of two places called Yelverton, in Norfolk or Devon. Medieval examples of the surname are from the Norfolk place, but the modern surname in Britain is associated mainly with Devon, where the earliest record of the surname is found in 1761, and is probably a substitution for   Elford  , an earlier form of the Devon placename. The Devon place, a hamlet in Buckland Monachorum, is not officially on record as <i>Yelverton</i> until the 19th century, when the Great Western Railway so named the station it built there in 1859. It is a dialect pronunciation of <i>Elverton</i>, which is first recorded in 1765 as an extended form of its medieval name <i>Elford</i> + <i>-ton</i> ‘town’. The Norfolk placename is recorded as <i>Ailuertuna</i> in 1086, and probably derives from the Old English personal name <i>Æthelfrith</i> or <i>Geldfrith</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Elford","meanings":["English: habitational name from Yelverton in Buckland Monachorum (Devon), recorded as <i>Elleford</i> in 1291 (see   Yelverton  ), named from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> or <i>elle</i>, <i>ellen</i> ‘elder tree’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. The name may also derive from any of the places called Elford in Staffordshire and Northumberland, both probably from the Old English personal name <i>Ella</i> + <i>ford</i>."]},{"name":"Yelvington","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Yelverton  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":82,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew de Yelverton was born about 1300, in Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Yelverton, was 20 and his mother, Maud Chappis, was 18. He married Margaret de Boson in 1326, in Whissonsett, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. In 1315, at the age of 16, his occupation is listed as lord of rackheath in Rackheath, Norfolk, England. He died about 1383, in his hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"ABT 1300–ABT 1383":"umbes 1300–umbes 1383","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1327–1377":"1327–1377","1281–1307":"1281–1307","1283–1307":"1283–1307","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1283":"1283","1281":"1281","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","ABT 1383":"umbes 1383","1301":"1301","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","ABT 1300":"umbes 1300","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rackheath, Norfolk County, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rackheath, Norfolk, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, England","Whissonsett, Norfolk, England":"Whissonsett, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1300–ABT 1383":"noin 1300–noin 1383","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1327–1377":"1327–1377","1281–1307":"1281–1307","1283–1307":"1283–1307","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1283":"1283","1281":"1281","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1304":"1304","ABT 1383":"noin 1383","1301":"1301","1377":"1377","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","ABT 1300":"noin 1300","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rackheath, Norfolk County, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Rackheath, Norfolk, England":"Rackheath, Norfolk, England","Whissonsett, Norfolk, England":"Whissonsett, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"ABT 1300–ABT 1383":"environ 1300–environ 1383","1300–1383":"1300–1383","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1327–1377":"1327–1377","1281–1307":"1281–1307",